---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import BackLink from "../components/astro/BackLink.astro";
import { SpectrumLineStage, SpectrumRingStage } from "../components/react/Huetone";

const formulaClasses = "bg-foreground/10 mx-0.5 px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded font-mono text-foreground tabular-nums";
---

<Layout
  title="Huetone — tonality through color"
  description="An interactive color map of the 12-tone chromatic scale. Click any note to set it as the tonic, pick a mode, and see which degrees belong to the scale."
>
  <main class="flex flex-col justify-center items-center gap-16 p-4 md:p-8 min-h-screen">
    <div class="flex flex-col items-center gap-4 max-w-3xl text-center">
      <h1 class="font-semibold text-3xl md:text-6xl text-balance">
        Huetone
      </h1>
      <h2 class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-balance">
        A theory of tonality, mapped through the language of color.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-muted text-sm md:text-base text-balance">
        Pick a mode, click any colour to set it as the tonic, scroll the line or
        the ring to shift through keys.
      </p>
    </div>

    <SpectrumLineStage client:load />
    <SpectrumRingStage client:load />

    <section class="flex flex-col gap-4 max-w-2xl text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        Each scale degree is bound to a fixed hue, and the colour wheel walks
        around the octave the same way harmonic function does. Shift the tonic
        and the pitches slide to new positions, but each degree keeps its
        colour.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because colours stay tied to function, every scale gets a recognisable
        colour signature you can spot across any key — the in-scale degrees
        light up while the rest fade. The line reads as sequence, the ring as
        cycle: two views of the same structure.
      </p>
    </section>

    <article class="flex flex-col gap-8 max-w-2xl">
      <h2 class="font-semibold text-2xl md:text-3xl text-balance">
        Physical basis
      </h2>

      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg md:text-xl text-balance">
          Pitch and colour are the same phenomenon
        </h3>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Sound is mechanical oscillation in air. Light is electromagnetic
          oscillation. Both are waves, and both are perceived as discrete
          qualities — a pitch, a colour — by sensory systems that respond to
          frequency. A note and a colour are therefore not analogous; they are
          the same physical phenomenon expressed in two different frequency
          bands. Mapping one onto the other is not a metaphor — it is a change
          of coordinates.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg md:text-xl text-balance">
          The visible spectrum is approximately one octave of light
        </h3>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          A musical octave is, precisely, a doubling of frequency:
          <code class={formulaClasses}>A4 = 440 Hz</code>,
          <code class={formulaClasses}>A5 = 880 Hz</code>,
          ratio
          <code class={formulaClasses}>2:1</code>.
          Two notes an octave apart sound like the same note in different
          registers because pitch is heard in log-frequency, and a doubling is
          one logarithmic step.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          The visible spectrum runs from roughly
          <code class={formulaClasses}>428 THz</code>
          (deep red) to
          <code class={formulaClasses}>789 THz</code>
          (deep violet). The ratio is
          <code class={formulaClasses}>789 / 428 ≈ 1.84</code>
          — just shy of two. We see almost exactly one octave of light. The
          next "octave up" from red is ultraviolet; the next "octave down" from
          violet is infrared.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          This is the structural fact Huetone rests on. The visible rainbow
          isn't an arbitrary stretch of frequencies — it is a single octave of
          the same wave phenomenon that gives us musical octaves.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg md:text-xl text-balance">
          Why measure in frequency, not wavelength
        </h3>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          Frequency is the physically fundamental quantity. It does not change
          when light enters a denser medium; wavelength does. The energy of a
          photon is <code class={formulaClasses}>E = hf</code>, proportional to frequency. Sound
          behaves the same way: a note's identity is its frequency, not the
          wavelength of the pressure wave, which depends on the speed of sound
          in the medium it travels through.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          When we say "the visible spectrum is an octave", we mean it in
          frequency space. The same is true of every claim about how the colour
          wheel divides — equal hue steps correspond to equal log-frequency
          steps, the same way the twelve equal-tempered semitones partition a
          musical octave.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h3 class="font-medium text-lg md:text-xl text-balance">
          Twelve into twelve
        </h3>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          The chromatic scale divides the musical octave into twelve
          equal-tempered semitones — each step is a frequency ratio of
          <code class={formulaClasses}>2<sup class="text-xs">1/12</sup> ≈ 1.0595</code>. Huetone divides the octave of visible
          light into twelve hue steps and binds each one to a scale degree.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted text-base md:text-lg leading-relaxed">
          The result is a literal translation, not a styled assignment. The
          tritone — six semitones from the tonic, half an octave away in
          frequency — lands on a hue half a hue-wheel away from the tonic's
          colour. The geometric structure of one octave is preserved across the
          mapping. The relationships between degrees in music are mirrored by
          the relationships between hues in vision, because both are the same
          arithmetic performed on the same kind of object: a single octave,
          divided in twelve.
        </p>
      </div>
    </article>

    <BackLink />
  </main>
</Layout>
